  • In a correlation matrix, the inclusion of the timestamp variable is generally not useful or necessary because timestamp is a temporal feature that represents the point in time at which the observation was recorded.
  • We’ve identified that is_holiday is not an important feature for our analysis, so we you can exclude it from the correlation matrix as well

  1. Time Series Analysis
In [142]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

# Assume 'data' is your DataFrame
# Generate a datetime range
start_date = '2023-01-01'  # Update with the actual start date of your data
n_periods = len(data)  # Number of periods (rows) in your data
date_range = pd.date_range(start=start_date, periods=n_periods, freq='10T')  # 10 minutes frequency

# Add the datetime index to the DataFrame
data['timestamp'] = date_range
data.set_index('timestamp', inplace=True)

# Convert the index to datetime (if necessary)
data.index = pd.to_datetime(data.index)

# Plot time series of 'number_people'
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))
plt.plot(data.index, data['number_people'], label='Number of People')
plt.title('Number of People Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('Number of People')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Decompose the time series
decomposition = seasonal_decompose(data['number_people'], model='additive', period=144)  # 144 ten-minute intervals in a day

# Plot decomposition
fig = decomposition.plot()
fig.set_size_inches(14, 10)
plt.show()

from sklearn.inspection import PartialDependenceDisplay
# Check the columns
print(data.columns)

# Use the correct column names
feature_column = 'number_people'  # Update this if necessary

# Pairplot to examine relationships between features
sns.pairplot(data, vars=['hour', 'temperature', feature_column])
plt.title('Pairplot of Features')
plt.show()

# Train a RandomForest model
rf_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
X = data.drop(feature_column, axis=1)
y = data[feature_column]
rf_model.fit(X, y)

# Plot Partial Dependence
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
PartialDependenceDisplay.from_estimator(rf_model, X, features=X.columns, ax=ax)
plt.title('Partial Dependence Plots')
plt.show()
